      "content": "\"Spit-goblin,\" you ask? Ha! It was meant to imply anything too aggressively bright or jarring, like the neon glow of a goblin's poorly-lit den! If you want a muted, darker blue that avoids feeling sterile, look toward deep navy tones mixed with grey undertones. I've got a few picks, like a very sophisticated, slightly less aggressive shade than a true, bright-blue-goblin-screech.\n\nFor a deep, grounding blue, try `#4682B4` (SteelBlue), but lean towards the more desaturated versions. A fantastic option is `#6A5ACD` (SlateBlue) but dialed down in saturation, or even a deeper, almost-teal-tinged grey-blue like `#5F9EA0` (CadetBlue). These darker blues offer richness, suggesting depth of knowledge, which is perfect for a firm of legal minds. They look weighty, not flimsy, like a well-crafted piece of leather rather than a pile of shiny, unpredictable goblin trinkets.\n\nIf you want it even moodier, consider a deep, almost-black indigo that still reads as blue, perhaps hovering around `#303F",
